{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_beargrass_ver01/data/sn86075096/00340581702/1949050101/1445.xml":{"full_text":"The Editor's Page\nFair Income With\nT HE real headache in the administra\ntion of any farm income support pro\ngram will come when production control be\ncomes necessary. That is why the depart\nment of agriculture has been exploring all\npossibilities of increasing consumption.\nIf actual market prices of food commod\nities are relatively low consumers will be\nable to buy more of these agricultural prod\nucts. And if more acreage of basic crops\ncan be diverted to livestock production the\nsurplus problem will be lessened to that\nextent.\nThese are the principal reasons behind\nthe provisions in the newly proposed farm\nprogram for permitting agricultural mar\nkets to seek their own level while farm in\ncomes are maintained through compensa\ntory payments.\nIf outlets for surplus farm commodities\ncannot be provided through increased con\nsumption by humans, animals and for in\ndustrial purposes then profitable income\nlevels can be maintained only through pro\nduction controls and marketing quotas. And\nMontana's Growing\nJ^IVESTOCK numbers showed a substan\ntial increase in Montana in 1948 and\nthere are indications that this upward trend\nwill continue. The federal agricultural sta\ntistician for Montana reported that cattle\nnumbers totaled 1,995,000 head on Jan. 1,\n1949, 8 percent over the year previous and\n33 percent greater than the 10-year average,\n1938-47.\nMontana registered the largest gain in\ncattle numbers during the past year of all\nstates excepting Iowa and Kansas. Texas\nshowed the greatest loss with a reduction\nof 192,000. In swine numbers Montana also\nmade a gain of 18 percent over the year\nbefore, with a total of 229,000 as compared\nwith 194,000 in 1948.\nThe ranges are probably stocked to\nnormal carrying capacity now and it is\ndoubtful whether there will be much further\nincrease in cattle on the regularly estab\nlished stock ranches during the next few\nyears. With a return of normal grass years\nthere may be some reduction. But some of\nthe increase in cattle numbers has occurred\nWheat Quotas\nS OMETIME in the next 60 days the secre\ntary of agriculture must decide whether\nit will be necessary to apply marketing\nquotas and acreage allotments with respect\nto wheat. Under the law he must proclaim\nmarketing quotas by July 1 and acreage\nallotments by July 15 if they are to be car\nried out with respect to next year's produc\ntion.\nThe prospective supply of wheat is just\nabout at the level that would require the\nannouncement of quotas and the holding of\na producer referendum to see whether such\ncontrols would be approved. If crop con\nditions in the wheat region should deterio\nrate to any marked degree during the next\nerably more drastic than those in effect in\nthe prewar era of AAA regulation.\nMinimum Regulation\no\nthese restrictions would have to be consid\nThere was very little actual production\ncontrol through the acreage allotment sys\ntem as administered in the '30s. Generally\nspeaking the land taken out of production\nthen was the most improductive acreage\non the farm. Production was maintained\ni i j\nat about normal levels by better tillage and\nother improved practices on the remaining\nacreage. That is why it is conceded that any\nproduction control in the future would have\nto be accompanied by strict marketing\nquotas. And rigid enforcement of market\ntion to which congress will be trying to find\nthe answer in the months ahead.\nmg quota regulations would be extremely\ndifficult. It would require a great deal of\ngovernment red tape and an army of super\nvisors.\nThe kind of support program that most\nfarmers and stockgrowers want is one that\nwill maintain income at levels that will give\nproducers equitable buying power with a\nminimum of regulation. That is the ques\nLivestock Industrv\non wheat farms as well as on irrigated\nman's editorial staff interviewed a number\nof central Montana farmers recently and\nfarms, and that is where future increases\nseem likely to materialize,\nA member of Montana Farmer-Stock\nasked them what they planned to do with\nexcess wheat land in case a wheat surplus\nsituation develops. Almost invariably the\nanswer was \"crested wheat grass,\nwhen asked what they planned to do with\nparts of the state in a corn-hog combination\nnow that some of the new hybrid strains\nthe crested wheat grass, they replied \"cattle/\nThere is also increasing interest in some\nhave demonstrated their adaptability to\nMontana conditions. Barley is also receiving\nincreasing consideration as a feed crop.\nImportant factors in the growing inter\nest in greater livestock production in Mon\ntana are the improved local marketing situa\ntion and the strong demand for livestock\nfrom the urban centers of the west coast\narea.\nand Allotments?\nfew weeks quotas would be avoided. They\nmight be avoided anyway if the administra\ntion should make a rather liberal estimate\n0 f consumption during the next marketing\nyear.\nBut if crop conditions should improve it\nwould be difficult to dodge the quota an\nnouncement. And if it were avoided by\nfancy pencil work still more serious surplus\nproblems might result a year from now.\nAdministrative work is under way in\nprogram, or both, can be put into effect\nwithout delay if that decision is reached.\nMontana and other important wheat pro\nducing states so that the quota or allotment\nStraws \u00een the Wind\nA two-price system for corn has been\nin effect since last October. The U. S. farm\nprice for corn averaged $1.20 a bushel from\nNovember through February. This was 24\ncents a bushel below the corn loan rate,\nHeavy exports have kept the wheat market\nprice about even with the loan rate. But\nmarket observers predict a two-price system\nfor wheat next fall, with the local market\nat least several cents a bushel under the\nloan basis. Better have enough farm stor\nage space to take full advantage of the loan\nplan.\nWhen the 1950 census is taken farmers\nand ranchers will be asked t0 \u00a3ill out the\nagricultural schedules before the\ncensus\ntaker arrives. The questionnaires will be\nmailed in advance of April 1, 1950. The cen\nsus bureau believes this method will be\nmore convenient for rural people and that\nthe information secured will be more accu\nrate because the farmer will have time to\nconsult his records more carefully. When\nthe taker arrives he will pick up the* agri\ncultural schedule and at the same time fill\nout the form for the population census.\nIt is understood that the unit limitation\nin the new Brannan farm income support\nplan designed to curb large-scale producers\nhas been dropped. The secretary and his\nassociates came to the conclusion that it\nwould be too difficult to administer, would\nleave too much production out of the con\ntrol program and might be declared uncon\nstitutional by the supreme court.\nMost economists now agree that the re\ncession will be of moderate degree because\nthere are so many supporting factors-in the\neconomic picture such as stabilized wage\nscales, farm support program, rearmament\nactivity, social security payments and per\nmanent increase in consumer demand due\nlarger population. Economists don't al\nways guess right but they have considerable\nbasis for their present forecasts.\nbarberry eradication program was started\nin 1918. The annual saving that has resulted\namounts to about $20,000,000. This is more\nthan the total cost of the barberry campaign\nduring the entire period since 1918,\n\nWheat losses due to black stem rust\nhave been reduced 50 percent since the\nMontana ranked 5th among the states\nin acreage planted to wheat in 1948 with\na total of 4,739,000. In barley it also ranked\n5th with 868,000 acres. The state's 119,000\nacres of flax put it in 6th place with respect\nto that crop,\n\nWhether the recession is to be moderate\nor severe, it is highly important for farmers\nand stockgrowers to strive for increased\nefficiency and lower operating costs.\nMontana Farmer-Stockman\n\u2014COVERS MONTANA AND NORTHERN WYOMING\u2014\nOFFICE: 1*1 4th St. N.. Great Falls, Montana.\nLESTER COLE\nDON R. BOSLEY\nLARRY GILL\nJERRY LESTER\nEditor and Manager\nAssistant Editor\nLivestock Editor\nRoving Reporter\nDepartment Editors: AMY MARTIN, Rural Homes Depart\nment: DR. HOWARD WELCH, Veterinary Department;\nRALPH D. MERCER, Soils and Crops; H. E. CUSHMAN,\nPoultry; I. W. DICKERSON, Farm Mechanics: DR. JOHN\nW. HOLLAND, Thoughts on Lite: GILBERT GUSLER.\nMarket Analyst.\nAdvertising Representatives: Western Associated Farm\nPapers\u2014CHICAGO 4: Fred Tool, National Adv. Manager,\n28 E. Jackson; NEW YORK 18: John W. Pox, Manager.\n500 Filth Avenue: SAN FRANCISCO 5: J. J. Mattus.\nManager. 707 Sharon Building.\nMember \u00bb1 Associated Farm Papers. Audit Bureau \u00bbt\nCirculations and Agricultural Publishers Association\nSUBSCRIPTION PRICE\u2014$3 lor live years. J2 lor three\nyears. $1 for one year: Canadian, one year. J2.00.\nRENEWALS AND CHANGES\u2014II the date on your label\nis not changed within three weeks after sending in\nyour remittance, please write us. II you wish a change\nIn address, give both new and old postoflices.\nADVERTISING\u2014Pull information regarding advertising\nrates, etc., sent on application. Subscribers are requested\nto mention promptly to us any advertiser who falls to\nlive up to his advertising agreement.\nVoL 3\u00ab, He. 17","height":"15990","width":"11226"}}
